(1) No quaestio could or ever did inflict the punishment of death.

(2) Suetonius, in order to show the leniency of Augustus, describes him as dealing in the following way with a man caught in the act of parricide. The Emperor wished to get him off the punishment of the sack, and therefore put to him the leading question, ‘ You surely did not kill your father?’ because only those who confessed their quilt received this punishment.⁷1 In such a case the criminal might answer ‘ No,’ and then be tried and punished in the ordinary way, viz. by exile and confiscation.
